{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_c7bc46d6d35844098edb3f0a","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Contributing\n2\t\n3\tInterested in contributing to `proselint`? Great — there are plenty of ways you\n4\tcan help. In the following sections, we describe how you can help us build\n5\t`proselint` into the greatest writing tool in the world.\n6\t\n7\t## Skills\n8\t\n9\t### Coding\n10\t\n11\tHave coding skills? You can:\n12\t\n13\t- Implement a new piece of advice in the linter. In our issue tracker on GitHub,\n14\t  we maintain an ever-growing [list of rules] that have been extracted from\n15\t  expert advice on writing. Some of these are one-liners that will take only a\n16\t  moment to complete; others are full-blown research projects. Use existing\n17\t  checks as a guide for creating your own. Then open a pull request.\n18\t- Fix [bugs].\n19\t- Improve [performance].\n20\t- Write tests. Our test coverage is too low. Keeping out false alarms is key to\n21\t  the tool's success and anything we can do to uncover false alarms and prevent\n22\t  regressions is thus key to the tool's success.\n23\t\n24\t[list of rules]: https://github.com/amperser/proselint/labels/cat:%20new-check\n25\t[bugs]: https://github.com/amperser/proselint/labels/type:%20fix\n26\t[performance]: https://github.com/amperser/proselint/labels/type:%20perf\n27\t\n28\t### Writing and editing\n29\t\n30\tHave writing or editing skills? You can:\n31\t\n32\t- Extract rules from expert sources of advice. Read through some entries of a\n33\t  book like *Garner's Modern American usage*, find rules that are feasible to\n34\t  implement, and then [open a Check Request issue]. Here's an [example] of a\n35\t  successfully extracted rule.\n36\t- Find false positives. Run `proselint` over your favourite books or magazine\n37\t  articles — maybe even your own writing — and find places where `proselint`\n38\t  says there's an error, but in reality, there is none. [Open a False Positive\n39\t  issue] and describe the problem.\n40\t- Improve the copy or documentation surrounding the project and within its code.\n41\t\n42\t[open a Check Request issue]: https://github.com/amperser/proselint/issues/new?template=check-request.md\n43\t[example]: https://github.com/amperser/proselint/issues/163\n44\t[Open a False Positive issue]: https://github.com/amperser/proselint/issues/new?template=false-positive.md\n45\t\n46\t## Process\n47\t\n48\t### Prerequisites\n49\t\n50\tBefore you spend valuable time contributing to Proselint, please first discuss\n51\tthe change you wish to make with us. The best way to do this is by filing an\n52\tissue with your proposal, since you'll need an issue number to refer to in your\n53\tpull request. Alternatively, you can skip this if an issue relating to your\n54\tchanges already exists.\n55\t\n56\tNext, ensure your environment is prepared. If you're using [Nix], this is as\n57\tsimple as running `nix develop`. For other systems, you'll need to install\n58\t[`uv`], and then run `uv sync --locked --dev --all-extras --group test` for the\n59\tfull suite of development and testing tools.\n60\t\n61\t[Nix]: https://nixos.org\n62\t[`uv`]: https://docs.astral.sh/uv\n63\t\n64\t### Workflow\n65\t\n66\t1. Fork and clone this repository.\n67\t2. Create a new branch in your fork based off the **main** branch.\n68\t3. Make your changes.\n69\t4. Commit your changes, and push them.\n70\t5. Submit a pull request.\n71\t\n72\t### Linting and Testing\n73\t\n74\tWe use [Poe] as a job runner. This makes the process of linting and testing your\n75\tchanges in the same way they'll be verified in CI trivial. Please do ensure\n76\tthese pass before you submit a pull request to keep your changes consistent with\n77\tour codebase.\n78\t\n79\t- **Linting**: `uv run poe lint`\n80\t- **Formatting**: `uv run poe format`\n81\t- **Testing**: `uv run poe test`\n82\t\n83\t[Poe]: https://poethepoet.natn.io\n84\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9b27b3bf-dbb4-4875-9866-3bff8f3c05f2","uuid":"30f4b7c5-8c9c-45c4-a562-4da2eae5e1a9","timestamp":"2026-04-06T19:54:09.440Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/CONTRIBUTING.md","content":"# Contributing\n\nInterested in contributing to `proselint`? Great — there are plenty of ways you\ncan help. In the following sections, we describe how you can help us build\n`proselint` into the greatest writing tool in the world.\n\n## Skills\n\n### Coding\n\nHave coding skills? You can:\n\n- Implement a new piece of advice in the linter. In our issue tracker on GitHub,\n  we maintain an ever-growing [list of rules] that have been extracted from\n  expert advice on writing. Some of these are one-liners that will take only a\n  moment to complete; others are full-blown research projects. Use existing\n  checks as a guide for creating your own. Then open a pull request.\n- Fix [bugs].\n- Improve [performance].\n- Write tests. Our test coverage is too low. Keeping out false alarms is key to\n  the tool's success and anything we can do to uncover false alarms and prevent\n  regressions is thus key to the tool's success.\n\n[list of rules]: https://github.com/amperser/proselint/labels/cat:%20new-check\n[bugs]: https://github.com/amperser/proselint/labels/type:%20fix\n[performance]: https://github.com/amperser/proselint/labels/type:%20perf\n\n### Writing and editing\n\nHave writing or editing skills? You can:\n\n- Extract rules from expert sources of advice. Read through some entries of a\n  book like *Garner's Modern American usage*, find rules that are feasible to\n  implement, and then [open a Check Request issue]. Here's an [example] of a\n  successfully extracted rule.\n- Find false positives. Run `proselint` over your favourite books or magazine\n  articles — maybe even your own writing — and find places where `proselint`\n  says there's an error, but in reality, there is none. [Open a False Positive\n  issue] and describe the problem.\n- Improve the copy or documentation surrounding the project and within its code.\n\n[open a Check Request issue]: https://github.com/amperser/proselint/issues/new?template=check-request.md\n[example]: https://github.com/amperser/proselint/issues/163\n[Open a False Positive issue]: https://github.com/amperser/proselint/issues/new?template=false-positive.md\n\n## Process\n\n### Prerequisites\n\nBefore you spend valuable time contributing to Proselint, please first discuss\nthe change you wish to make with us. The best way to do this is by filing an\nissue with your proposal, since you'll need an issue number to refer to in your\npull request. Alternatively, you can skip this if an issue relating to your\nchanges already exists.\n\nNext, ensure your environment is prepared. If you're using [Nix], this is as\nsimple as running `nix develop`. For other systems, you'll need to install\n[`uv`], and then run `uv sync --locked --dev --all-extras --group test` for the\nfull suite of development and testing tools.\n\n[Nix]: https://nixos.org\n[`uv`]: https://docs.astral.sh/uv\n\n### Workflow\n\n1. Fork and clone this repository.\n2. Create a new branch in your fork based off the **main** branch.\n3. Make your changes.\n4. Commit your changes, and push them.\n5. Submit a pull request.\n\n### Linting and Testing\n\nWe use [Poe] as a job runner. This makes the process of linting and testing your\nchanges in the same way they'll be verified in CI trivial. Please do ensure\nthese pass before you submit a pull request to keep your changes consistent with\nour codebase.\n\n- **Linting**: `uv run poe lint`\n- **Formatting**: `uv run poe format`\n- **Testing**: `uv run poe test`\n\n[Poe]: https://poethepoet.natn.io\n","numLines":84,"startLine":1,"totalLines":84}}}
